content.theory:
## Input Validation

The first rule of API security: **never trust client input**. Validate everything — types, lengths, formats, ranges.

### Validation Strategy

```javascript
// Manual validation:
app.post('/api/users', (req, res) => {
  const errors = [];
  const { name, email } = req.body;

  if (!name || typeof name !== 'string') 
    errors.push({ field: 'name', message: 'Required string' });
  else if (name.length < 2 || name.length > 50)
    errors.push({ field: 'name', message: '2-50 characters' });

  if (!email || !/^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/.test(email))
    errors.push({ field: 'email', message: 'Valid email required' });

  if (errors.length > 0)
    return res.status(422).json({ errors });

  // Safe to proceed
});
```

### Schema Validation Libraries

Manual validation doesn't scale. Use libraries:

```javascript
// With Zod:
const createUserSchema = z.object({
  name: z.string().min(2).max(50),
  email: z.string().email(),
  role: z.enum(['user', 'admin']).default('user')
});

app.post('/api/users', (req, res) => {
  const result = createUserSchema.safeParse(req.body);
  if (!result.success) {
    return res.status(422).json({ errors: result.error.issues });
  }
  // result.data is typed and validated
});
```

### Security Implications

| Without Validation | Risk |
|---|---|
| No type check | NoSQL injection, type confusion |
| No length limit | DoS (1GB name field) |
| No sanitization | XSS in stored data |
| No enum check | Privilege escalation (role: 'admin') |

